# Gating system

## Purpose

This `.gates/` folder holds every quality gate the spec-writer +
arc-runner workflow can require for a slice in this repo. A gate
is a YAML descriptor (`*.gates`) that names a command, a pass
condition, and the file globs it applies to. The arc-runner
executes the gates a slice has selected; the spec-writer's
gate-keeper agent proposes which gates each spec should include.

## Layout

Two-level structure:

- **Root-level gates** (this folder, `.gates/*.gates`) -- universal
  checks that apply to every slice regardless of project. Today:
  `impl-log-structure.gates`, `state-of-world-structure.gates`.
  Each enforces a documentation shape the spec-writer relies on,
  so excluding them would break the workflow itself.
- **Per-group gates** (`.gates/<group>/`) -- project-specific or
  subsystem-specific checks. Each group folder carries its own
  `.gates-md` describing the group's purpose and naming
  conventions. Today: `.gates/Berreman/` (F# numerical optics
  solver build / test gates).

## When to add a new gate

1. **Root vs group.** If the gate applies to every slice in every
   project, place it at root. If it targets a specific project
   (Berreman, a future side project under this repo), place it
   under the matching `<group>/` subfolder.
2. **New group?** If no existing group fits, create
   `.gates/<new-group>/` with its own `.gates-md` (see the
   gate-keeper system prompt for the required shape). Pick the
   group name after the project / subsystem, not after a
   technology stack.
3. **Agent vs operator.** The gate-keeper agent authors descriptor
   drafts into `<spec-folder>/.proposed-gates/<group>/`. The
   operator reviews each draft in the spec-writer composer's
   gates panel and promotes it -- promotion moves the file into
   the matching `.gates/<group>/`. The agent never writes here
   directly.

## Naming

Descriptor files use the gate name as the file stem
(`<name>.gates`). Gate names are unique across the whole `.gates/`
tree -- the bundle's `gates:` array references gates by name only,
so two descriptors sharing a name would create an ambiguity the
scanner rejects. Within a group, use a shared prefix when several
gates target the same sub-area so the ordering in any arc-runner
manifest stays readable.
